{
  "texts": [
    "It is on the basis of the probabilistic knowledge of others' voting behaviours that a voter decides to vote tactically, i.e., to choose a less preferred outcome set in order to optimise the overall result.",
    "We claim that the notion of core voter knowledge should be revised to include strategic knowledge, in the form of probabilistic knowledge of how other voters are likely to vote.",
    "Polling results are also conducive to core voter knowledge, insofar as they help voters make comparative assessments between candidates.",
    "The knowledge of what similarly-situated voters are likely to vote can indeed be a useful shortcut to knowing how to vote.",
    "Polls provide an indication of a candidate's viability and thus ease decision-making by reducing the number of viable options (Aldrich 1980; Lau and Redlawsk 2001)."
  ]
}